ce:section.ce:para:
L-Trp was introduced to partial burning in a one-pot method (Scheme 1
                     ) by varying temperature and time and optimized the parameters for maximum fluorescence indicating the presence and formation of C-dots. UV–visible absorption studies were performed to detect the presence of L-Trp in the prepared C-dots (Fig. 1
                     A). The spectrum of L-Trp-C-dots indicated the characteristic absorption peaks of L-Trp. The absorption peaks at 219 nm and 279 nm were attributed to π → π * transition of CC whereas the peak observed at 280 nm is attributed to the n → π * transition of CO, respectively [23,24] is an indication of intact functional groups even after the pyrolysis. After pyrolysis at 200 °C for 35 min, the L-Trp-C-dots were exposed to 365 nm UV light, which showed blue fluorescence, indicating the formation of C-dots (Fig. 1B). The prepared C-dots exhibit a fluorescence spectrum centered at 446.8 nm when excited at 370 nm as shown in Fig. 1C.
